

<section xml:id="sec-verifying-solutions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
 <title>Verifying Solutions</title>

 

 <p>
    Sometimes we are given proposed solutions to ODEs, and we must check whether they actually solve the ODE. To verify that <m>y(x)</m> is a solution to a differential equation, you must plug in <m>y</m> and its relevant derivatives into both sides of the equation and verify they equal each other.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-verify-solution">
    <title>Verifying a Solution</title>
    <p>
      Verify that <m>y(x) = Ce^{-x^3}</m> is a solution to <m>y' + 3x^2 y = 0</m>.
    </p>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Compute <m>y'</m>. Then plug the expressions for <m>y</m> and <m>y'</m> into the equation and check if the left and right sides are equal.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We compute:
        <ul>
          <li><m>y(x) = Ce^{-x^3}</m></li>
          <li>
            <p><m>y'(x) = -3x^2 Ce^{-x^3}</m></p>
            <solution>
              <title>Explanation: Computing <m>y'</m></title>
              <p>
                We find <m>y'</m> by using the chain rule on <m>e^{-x^3}</m>, which is a composition of <m>e^x</m> (outside function) with <m>-x^3</m> (the inside function). The derivative of the inside function equals <m>-3x^2</m>, which is why this expression is multiplied out in front when differentiating.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        Plugging into <m>y' + 3x^2 y = 0</m>:
        <me>y' + 3x^2 y = -3x^2 Ce^{-x^3} + 3x^2 \cdot Ce^{-x^3} = 0 = \text{RHS.} \checkmark</me>
        Therefore <m>y(x) = Ce^{-x^3}</m> is a solution.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

 <p> To get a better overall feel for what just took place in this example, play around with the slider in the graph below! </p> 
<figure xml:id="fig-verify-slider">
  <caption>
    The family of solutions <m>y = Ce^{-x^3}</m> to the ODE <m>y' + 3x^2y = 0</m>. Use the slider to change <m>C</m> and observe that no matter what value you choose, the verification always gives LHS = 0 = RHS!
  </caption>
  <interactive xml:id="interactive-verify-slider" iframe="interactive-verify-slider.html" width="80%" aspect="3:2">
    <static>
      <p>
        An interactive graph showing the solution curve <m>y = Ce^{-x^3}</m> with a slider for <m>C</m> from <m>-3</m> to <m>3</m>. The green expressions update to show the substitution into <m>y' + 3x^2y = 0</m>, always simplifying to 0. A red dot marks <m>y(0) = C</m>.
      </p>
    </static>
  </interactive>
</figure>
 <p>
     It's now try to practice this a bit more! Try each of the following examples on your own, and then check with the notes or video.
  </p>

 <activity xml:id="act-verifying-solutions">
  <title>Practice: Verifying Solutions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Try each of the following on your own before checking the solution. Use the hints if you get stuck.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <task xml:id="task-verify-tan">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Verify that <m>y(x) = \tan(x^3 + C)</m> is a solution to <m>y' = 3x^2(y^2 + 1)</m>. Then find the specific solution given the initial condition <m>y(0) = 1</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        To compute <m>y'</m>, recall that the derivative of <m>\tan</m> is <m>\sec^2</m>, and use the chain rule. The outside function is <m>\tan</m> and the inside function is <m>x^3 + C</m>.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <hint>
      <p>
        To find the specific solution: plug in <m>0</m> wherever you see <m>x</m> and <m>1</m> wherever you see <m>y</m> in <m>y(x) = \tan(x^3 + C)</m>.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
        <p>
          We have <m>y = \tan(x^3 + C)</m>, so by the chain rule:
          <me>y' = 3x^2\sec^2(x^3 + C).</me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Plugging into both sides of the ODE:
          <me>
            \underbrace{3x^2\sec^2(x^3+C)}_{\text{LHS} = y'} = \underbrace{3x^2(\tan^2(x^3+C)+1)}_{\text{RHS} = 3x^2(y^2+1)} 
          </me>
          Using the Pythagorean identity <m>\tan^2(\theta)+1 = \sec^2(\theta)</m>, the RHS simplifies:
          <me>
            \underbrace{3x^2\sec^2(x^3+C)}_{\text{LHS}} = \underbrace{3x^2\sec^2(x^3+C)}_{\text{RHS (simplified)}} \checkmark
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          For the specific solution, apply <m>y(0) = 1</m>:
        </p>
        <solution>
          <title>Finding <m>C</m></title>
          <p>
            <me>1 = \tan(0^3 + C) = \tan(C) \implies C = \frac{\pi}{4}.</me>
            So the specific solution is <m>y(x) = \tan\!\left(x^3 + \dfrac{\pi}{4}\right)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
        <p>
          <em>Note: technically there are other values of <m>C</m> (namely <m>\frac{\pi}{4} + n\pi</m>), but they ultimately give the same function <m>y</m>, as the tangent function is <m>\pi</m>-periodic.</em>
        </p>
      </solution>
  </task>
 <task xml:id="task-verify-cos">
  <statement>
    <p>
      For what values of <m>m</m> is <m>\cos(mx)</m> a solution to <m>y'' = -4y</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Start by verifying <m>y = \cos(mx)</m> as usual. There will be an additional step to solve for the values of <m>m</m> that ensure LHS = RHS.
    </p>
  </hint>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <alert>Verify when <m>y = \cos(mx)</m> is a solution.</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
      First note that if <m>y = \cos(mx)</m>, then <m>y'' = -m^2\cos(mx)</m>.
    </p>
    <solution>
      <title>Computing <m>y''</m></title>
      <p>
        Differentiating <m>y = \cos(mx)</m> twice via the chain rule:
        <me>y' = -m\sin(mx), \quad y'' = -m^2\cos(mx).</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <p>
      Plug <m>y = \cos(mx)</m> and <m>y'' = -m^2\cos(mx)</m> into <m>y'' = -4y</m> and solve for <m>m</m>.
      Try it out and check with the solution below!
    </p>
    <solution>
      <title>Solving for <m>m</m></title>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>y'' \amp= -4y</mrow>
          <mrow>-m^2\cos(mx) \amp= -4\cos(mx)</mrow>
          <mrow>-m^2 \amp= -4</mrow>
          <mrow>m \amp= \pm 2.</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
    <p>
      So <m>\cos(2x)</m> is a solution. (Note: <m>\cos(-2x) = \cos(2x)</m> since cosine is an even function, so these are the same solution.)
    </p>
  </solution>
</task>

  <task xml:id="task-verify-mc">
    <title>Check Your Understanding</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let's explore the previous example a bit more. Which of the following are solutions to <m>y'' = -4y</m>? Select all that apply.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="yes">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>y = \sin(2x)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! You can verify: <m>y'' = -4\sin(2x) = -4y</m>. See the remark below for why this is no coincidence!
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>y = \cos(2x)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! This is exactly what we just found above with <m>m = 2</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p><m>y = 3\sin(2x) + 5\cos(2x)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Correct! And this is no coincidence — see the remark below for why combinations like this always work.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>y = e^{2x}</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not a solution. If <m>y = e^{2x}</m>, then <m>y'' = 4e^{2x} = 4y</m>, not <m>-4y</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p><m>y = \cos(x)</m></p></statement>
        <feedback>
          <p>
            Not a solution. If <m>y = \cos(x)</m>, then <m>y'' = -\cos(x) = -y</m>, not <m>-4y</m>. This corresponds to <m>m = 1</m>, but we need <m>m = \pm 2</m>.
          </p>
        </feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
  </task>

  <task xml:id="task-verify-ert">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find all <m>r</m> so that <m>e^{rt}</m> is a solution to <m>y'' + 5y' + 6y = 0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        After substituting <m>y</m>, <m>y'</m>, and <m>y''</m> into the equation, what can you divide by to simplify?
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Let <m>y(t) = e^{rt}</m>. Then by the chain rule:
        <me>y'(t) = re^{rt}, \quad y''(t) = r^2e^{rt}.</me>
        Plugging into <m>y'' + 5y' + 6y = 0</m>:
        <me>r^2e^{rt} + 5re^{rt} + 6e^{rt} = 0.</me>
        Dividing both sides by <m>e^{rt}</m> (which we can do since <m>e^{rt}</m> is never zero):
        <me>r^2 + 5r + 6 = 0.</me>
        Notice there is no more <m>t</m> variable — we just have a quadratic in <m>r</m>! Factoring:
        <me>(r+3)(r+2) = 0 \implies r = -3, \; r = -2.</me>
        So <m>y = e^{-3t}</m> and <m>y = e^{-2t}</m> are both solutions.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>

</activity>
  <remark xml:id="rem-other-solutions">
    <title>Other Solutions to <m>y'' = -4y</m></title>
    <p>
      In the previous activity we found that <m>\cos(2x)</m> is a solution to <m>y'' = -4y</m>. But there are others! In fact, <m>y = \sin(2x)</m> is also a solution:
      <me>y' = 2\cos(2x), \quad y'' = -4\sin(2x) = -4y \checkmark</me>
      More generally, <m>y(x) = a\sin(2x) + b\cos(2x)</m> is a solution for any constants <m>a, b</m>. 
      This turns out be quite fundamental for this course, and we will explore this later on! 
    </p>
  </remark>

  <figure xml:id="video-verifying-solns">
        <caption>This video goes through the content of this page.</caption>
        <video youtube="1-_O7BVDqX8" width="100%" preview="default"/>
    </figure>
</section>